{
  "title": "War as an Autopoietic System",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8dace96ed73d0cbb",
      "text": "Whatever official and factual causes may be named for the start of a war, they usually have little to do with the mechanisms that ensure its continuation. War creates its own reasons once it has begun. In this respect, it can be considered an [[Autopoietic System]]. Like other autopoietic systems, war only persists as long as the operations that characterize it continue."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "76415db1bff102ad",
      "text": "These operations are actions that harm the enemy and threaten his survival, or at least are interpreted that way by him. They seem to be explained in each case - from the internal perspective of the participants by the damaging intention of the enemy. They cross the boundaries of passive negation, i.e. of non-consent and communicated contradiction; there is an exchange of actively negating actions between the two sides."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "add66012c3561426",
      "text": "[...] And since wars are made up of cruelties inflicted on the opponent, cruelties are likely to produce cruelties. Each of the two parties sees itself in the victim role and has unpaid bills to settle. If both sides do this, a revenge dynamic is created, and there are no available rules and mechanisms within the system to end it. There may be pauses for exhaustion, but as long as the memory of the suffering each has endured is perpetuated and the parties involved think they can force the opponent to pay the price they have set, such a warlike pattern of relationships and interactions can continue in principle forever. The wars in the Balkans, which have flared up again and again over centuries, are evidence of this. They are not new wars, but the continuation of an old, unfinished war."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "563834916ce55e1c",
      "text": "[…] If the [[Goal]] of war is to win, the worry of losing is a reason to continue the fight. The goal of the war is then to prevent the decision or to maintain the state of indecision. As long as a war is not lost, so long there is hope of winning somehow after all."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "eafaab15b6a12064",
      "text": "It is easier not to lose a war than to win it. As long as the defeated in the fight is not destroyed, he has, so to speak, the right of veto over the victory of the superior. He has to acknowledge his defeat (surrender) and thus receives the power of definition over victory and defeat. If the war is not ended communicatively by acknowledging defeat, there is no victor. The superior must expect that the inferior will resume hostilities. Only his total annihilation can lead to a victory independent of the loser's consent."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ceda788c7200e70e",
      "text": "This is probably not only one of the reasons for the emergence of \"final solution\" and \"final victory\" ideas, but also one of the mechanisms that ensure that wars do not end, even if no one remembers for a long time why they were started."
    },
